# [BFD](../wg/bfd.html)

## Summary

The Bidirectional Forwarding Detection (BFD) Working Group met to discuss the advancement of its core specifications to Full Internet Standard (per RFC 2026). The agenda focused on reviewing status updates, discussing outstanding errata, collecting implementation reports, and addressing technical edge cases for several bis-drafts: [draft-ietf-bfd-rfc5880bis](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-bfd-rfc5880bis/), [draft-ietf-bfd-rfc5881bis](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-bfd-rfc5881bis/), [draft-ietf-bfd-rfc5882-bis](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-bfd-rfc5882-bis/), [draft-ietf-bfd-rfc5883-bis](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-bfd-rfc5883-bis/), and [draft-ietf-bfd-rfc5884-bis](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-bfd-rfc5884-bis/).

---

## Key Discussion Points

### 1. Working Group Status and Standards Advancement
**Presenter:** Jeff Haas
* **Slides:** [Chairs slides](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-bfd-chairs-slides-00)
* **WG Role & Scope:** The WG has rechartered and finished its lingering milestones. BFD increasingly serves as a consulting body for other IETF working groups utilizing BFD. Overlapping state machines in strict-mode implementations (e.g., OSPF and BGP [draft-ietf-idr-bgp-bfd-strict-mode]) have occasionally caused interop issues, highlighting the need to maintain clear procedural coordination as specified in `draft-ietf-bfd-rfc5882-bis`.
* **Standard Advancement (RFC 2026):** To advance the base documents to Full Internet Standard, the WG must address outstanding errata, demonstrate at least two independent interoperating implementations for every active feature, and remove unused features. 
* **Discussion:** Ketan Talaulikar noted that features supported by only a single implementation should be evaluated for removal during the advancement to Full Standard.

---

### 2. Base Specifications Updates: RFC 5880bis and RFC 5881bis
**Presenter:** Reshad Rahman (on behalf of Alvaro Retana)
* **Slides:** [rfc5880bis Update (BFD)](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-bfd-rfc5880bis-update-bfd-00) & [rfc5881bis Update (BFD for IPv4 and IPv6 (Single Hop))](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-bfd-rfc5881bis-update-bfd-for-ipv4-and-ipv6-single-hop-00)
* **[draft-ietf-bfd-rfc5880bis](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-bfd-rfc5880bis/):** Base document references have been updated to XMLv3. Verified errata are merged, and three implementation reports have been received. 
  * *Demand Mode Support:* While initially believed to have only one implementation, Demand Mode is supported across three distinct Cisco codebases. Matthew Bocci indicated he would check Nokia’s implementation status for Demand Mode.
* **[draft-ietf-bfd-rfc5881bis](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-bfd-rfc5881bis/):** References are updated to XMLv3. No implementation status reports have been submitted yet.
* **Operational Considerations:** Jeff Haas pointed out that BFD’s operational sections are historically brief and may face scrutiny under current IESG criteria (e.g., RFC 5706bis). Ketan Talaulikar suggested keeping changes within the bis-draft minimal, and if necessary, writing a separate Best Current Practice (BCP) or Informational document to address BFD operations without delaying the standards advancement.
* **Implementation Report Publication:** Jeffrey Zhang asked where reports are published. Jeff Haas clarified they are appended directly to the draft’s appendix using standard RFC formats.

