### 3. Application and Multihop Updates: RFC 5882-bis and RFC 5883-bis
**Presenter:** Xiao Min
* **Slides:** [rfc5882-bis and rfc5883-bis](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-bfd-rfc-5882-bis-and-rfc-5883-bis-00)
* **[draft-ietf-bfd-rfc5882-bis](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-bfd-rfc5882-bis/):** Four editorial errata were integrated (such as correcting "Label Switched Path" to "Link State Packet" where appropriate and fixing section references). ZTE provided an implementation report indicating they do not support some `SHOULD`-level features (e.g., session state hysteresis, local admin down notification for static routes, and Graceful Restart interactions). Jeff Haas confirmed that other implementations (such as HPE and Juniper) support these features, so they do not need to be removed from the standard.
* **[draft-ietf-bfd-rfc5883-bis](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-bfd-rfc5883-bis/):** ZTE provided an implementation status report. 
  * *Echo Function over Multiple Hops:* A mailing list discussion addressed the restriction that Echo "MUST NOT" be used over multiple hops. Reshad Rahman proposed text relaxing this restriction for environments where intermediate nodes will not inappropriately return the Echo packet. 
  * Jeff Haas noted that the original restriction was imposed by Transport ADs to prevent Echo-based DDoS attacks. He added that tunneling (like SRv6) effectively acts as single-hop at the inner layer, which may satisfy security considerations.
  * John Scudder and Mariya discussed the "in other words" explanatory text proposed for the draft. Mariya advocated keeping this text, noting it provides a valuable sanity check for implementers reading the specification for the first time.

