### 4. MPLS Specifications: RFC 5884-bis
**Presenter:** Prasad Miriyala
* **Slides:** [RFC 5884-bis](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-bfd-rfc-5884-bis-00)
* **[draft-ietf-bfd-rfc5884-bis](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-bfd-rfc5884-bis/):** This draft merges RFC 5884 and RFC 7726 to resolve and clarify BFD execution over MPLS LSPs in ECMP scenarios. Three errata have been incorporated, and an implementation template has been added to the appendix.
* **Discriminator Inconsistency:** Greg Mirsky raised an edge case: what should occur if a remote BFD entity returns an LSP Echo reply containing its local discriminator *after* it has already begun transmitting BFD control packets. Prasad Miriyala recalled that prevailing implementation behavior is to silently ignore the Echo reply's discriminator and give precedence to the control packet. Jeff Haas requested that this behavior be formally audited across implementations to ensure the text is updated accurately.
* **IPv6 Loopback Addresses:** Greg Mirsky brought up the ongoing discussion regarding using loopback addresses for IPv6. Matthew Bocci recalled historical IESG pushback stating that IPv4-mapped loopback addresses (127/8) are not valid loopbacks in an IPv6 context. Matthew suggested that if current implementations actually use these addresses in production, the IPv6 specification itself may need correction rather than modifying BFD behavior.
* **Author Limit on Merged Drafts:** Merging RFC 5884 and RFC 7726 increases the author count. Jeff Haas confirmed that the IESG routinely waives the 5-author limit under merge circumstances.

